VIRAL GASTROENTERITIS UPDATE 2002 - UK & IRELAND(02)
**************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[The outbreaks of viral gastroenteritis included in these updates have the
characteristics of "winter vomiting disease", and are presumed to be caused
by Norwalk-like viruses (i.e., caliciviruses classified in the genus
_Norovirus_), although this is rarely confirmed microbiologically. The UK
and Ireland seem to be particularly prone at present to outbreaks of
"winter-vomiting" disease in institutional settings. - Mod.CP]
In these updates:
[1] England (Huntingdon)
[2] England (Reading)
[3] England (Bournemouth & Reading)
[4] Scotland (East Kilbride)
******
[1]
Date: Tue 22 Oct 2002
From: Luz Alba Fornells <luzalba@bioqmed.ufrj.br>
Source: BBC News Online, Tue 22 Oct 2002 [edited]
<http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/england/2351049.stm>

England: 4 Wards closed at Hospital in Huntingdon
--------------------------------------------------
More than a week after an outbreak of winter vomiting disease, 4 wards
remain closed at Hinchingbrooke Hospital in Huntingdon. This illness
particularly attacks hospital patients whose resistance is low. At the
start of last week, 2 medical wards were originally shut, but this soon
rose to 4. Children, elderly people, and pregnant women were being advised
not to go to the hospital, except in an emergency. On Tuesday morning a
spokeswoman for Hinchingbrooke Hospital said the situation was now improving.
Each ward needs to be isolated for 48 hours after the last episode.
Inpatient capacity manager Rachel Watt said the hospital was now hoping to
reopen 2 of the wards within the next 24 hours. Friends and relatives of
patients are being advised to check with the hospital before visiting.
Meanwhile, across the rest of the region the families of patients at
Kettering General Hospital and Milton Keynes General Hospital are still
being asked to avoid visits. The virus is still keeping several wards
closed at these hospitals.
--
Luz Alba Fornells, Ph.D.
Center for the Study of Emerging Infectious Diseases
Federal University of Rio de Janeiro, Brazil
<luzalba@bioqmed.ufrj.br>
